{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":126420,"duration_api_ms":125909,"num_turns":3,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"bcf2aa65-6d78-4e47-b419-a19c14d4af6a","total_cost_usd":0.39888115,"usage":{"input_tokens":4,"cache_creation_input_tokens":26464,"cache_read_input_tokens":80252,"output_tokens":1821,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":26464,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":4,"outputTokens":1821,"cacheReadInputTokens":80252,"cacheCreationInputTokens":26464,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.251071,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":88,"outputTokens":6825,"cacheReadInputTokens":578634,"cacheCreationInputTokens":44587,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.14781014999999997,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"All six amendments identify genuine defects in the milestone task-run completion subsystem. I verified each claim against the actual source code in service.rs, fs.rs, and model.rs. The core issue is a split between two completion paths (append-based record_bead_completion and mutate-based update_task_run) with inconsistent side effects, compounded by incorrect Skipped handling and insufficient matching granularity. All amendments should be accepted.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-1-83cc18bd","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified in source: update_task_run (service.rs:419-438) delegates directly to the FS adapter's update_task_run, which only rewrites task-runs.ndjson. It never touches MilestoneSnapshot (no call to write_snapshot) and never emits journal events (no call to append_event). By contrast, record_bead_completion (service.rs:352-384) correctly decrements in_progress_beads, increments completed/failed counters, clears active_bead, and emits journal events. Any caller using update_task_run to transition a Running entry to a terminal state will leave snapshot counters and active_bead permanently stale. This is a real state-consistency bug."},{"amendment_id":"fr-1-b88127a5","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed in source: service.rs lines 372-376 use a simple if/else where Succeeded maps to BeadCompleted and everything else (including Skipped) maps to BeadFailed. Meanwhile, the progress counter match (lines 354-362) only handles Succeeded and Failed with an empty _ => {} arm, so Skipped decrements in_progress_beads but never increments any terminal counter. This means skipped beads vanish from accounting while emitting a misleading BeadFailed event. Both the semantic mislabeling and the counter gap are real bugs, especially since model.rs explicitly defines Skipped as a terminal state via is_terminal()."},{"amendment_id":"fr-1-931e3b47","decision":"accept","rationale":"The two APIs have contradictory write semantics: record_bead_completion appends a new TaskRunEntry with finished_at set (leaving the original Running entry untouched), while update_task_run mutates the existing entry in place. If both are called for the same bead run, the NDJSON file will contain the original Running entry (now mutated to terminal) plus a second appended terminal entry—doubling the completion record. The test update_task_run_modifies_outcome (fs.rs:908-962) only tests the update path in isolation. No test covers the combined scenario, and there is no documentation defining which path callers should use. This ambiguity is a maintainability defect that needs explicit resolution."},{"amendment_id":"fr-1-6940a2a3","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed: update_task_run in fs.rs (lines 2313-2367) reads the entire NDJSON file into memory, deserializes all entries, mutates one, and rewrites the whole file via write_atomic. The atomic write protects the final replacement but not the read-modify-write window. A concurrent append_task_run (which uses append_line) occurring between the read at line 2315 and the write at line 2367 will have its appended line silently dropped by the full-file rewrite. This is a real lost-update hazard. Even if current usage patterns make concurrent access unlikely, the lack of any file locking or even a documenting comment makes this a latent defect."},{"amendment_id":"fr-1-3c001aa9","decision":"accept","rationale":"This amendment correctly identifies the fundamental design inconsistency. record_bead_completion (lines 324-387) creates a complete completion record but appends a second row, leaving the original Running row in the lineage file—not ideal for a lineage-style record. update_task_run (lines 419-438) mutates the existing row in place (cleaner for lineage) but omits snapshot and journal updates entirely. Neither path alone is correct: one duplicates lineage entries, the other leaves state stale. Consolidating into a single completion flow that both mutates the existing task-run row and updates snapshot/journal is the right fix. This overlaps with fr-1-83cc18bd and fr-1-931e3b47 but frames the solution more precisely."},{"amendment_id":"fr-1-15b667eb","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed: fs.rs lines 2340-2350 match only on bead_id + project_id and take the last (most recent) match in reverse iteration. The run_id field exists on TaskRunEntry (model.rs line 277-278) specifically for per-run auditability, but it is completely ignored in the matching logic. If a bead is retried (which the test multiple_retries_visible_for_same_bead explicitly demonstrates as a supported pattern), update_task_run will always target the most recent entry for that bead+project pair, which may not be the intended run. The matching should incorporate run_id when present to ensure the correct attempt is updated."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"bd4df82e-0f1b-4cb1-bc29-598923e7f1f4"}
